Okay בוקר טוב <i>Boker tov</i>, today's דף <i>Daf</i> is ע״ג <i>Ayin Gimmel</i>, מנחות <i>Menachos</i> 73. We pick up with the new פרק <i>Perek</i> at the bottom of ע״ב עמוד ב׳ <i>Ayin Bet Amud Bet</i> and we're in the middle of describing the different ways in which מנחות <i>Menachos</i> were prepared, which have oil, which have קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> and so on. So ואלו מנחות נקמצות ושיריהן לכהנים <i>Ve-elu menachos nikmatzos u-shiyureihen la-kohanim</i>: the following מנחות <i>Menachos</i> you do קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> on and the remainder is eaten by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i>, which is of course a standard מנחה <i>Mincha</i>. מנחת הסולת והמחבת והמרחשת והחלות והרקיקין <i>Minchas hasoles ve-hamachavas ve-hamarcheshes ve-hachalos ve-harekikhin</i>: so all the מנחות <i>Menachos</i> mentioned there in the beginning of ויקרא <i>Vayikra</i>; flour, frying pan, more of a saucepan, loaves, wafers, which are the two variations of the מאפה תנור <i>Ma-afeh tanur</i>. מנחת עובדי כוכבים <i>Minchas ovdei kokhavim</i> if it's brought by non-Jews. מנחת נשים <i>Minchas nashim</i> brought by women, not clear why you would think that would be different, not made a different category in the תורה <i>Torah</i>. מנחת העומר מנחת חוטא ומנחת קנאות <i>Minchas ha-omer, minchas chotei, u-minchas kena'os</i>: last three are all out of barley. The מנחה <i>Mincha</i> of the עומר <i>Omer</i>, and which we've been discussing, the מנחה <i>Mincha</i> of the חוטא <i>Chotei</i> in the case of a קרבן עולה ויורד <i>Korban oleh ve-yored</i>, the end of פרשת ויקרא <i>Parshas Vayikra</i>, and a מנחת קנאות <i>Minchas kena'os</i> of the case of סוטה <i>Sotah</i>, and those are the ones that don't have oil and frankincense on them, the last two. רבי שמעון אומר <i>Rabbi Shimon omer</i>, רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> says: מנחת חוטא של כהנים נקמצת והקומץ קרב לעצמו והשיריים קרבים לעצמן <i>Minchas chotei shel kohanim nikmetzes ve-hakomets karev le-atsmo ve-hashiyurayim krevim le-atsman</i>. So one of the מנחות <i>Menachos</i> not mentioned in the first list was a מנחת כהן <i>Minchas kohen</i> because a מנחת כהן <i>Minchas kohen</i> is completely burned. And if it's completely burned, why do you need a קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>? The קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> is what goes on the fire and the remainder is eaten. So the assumption is no קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>, you just put it all on the fire. But רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> says no, you actually would do a קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> on a מנחת כהן <i>Minchas kohen</i> and you would offer up the קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> separately. There would be a meaning, a separate sort of ritual and significance to offering up the קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>, and then the remainder of the מנחה <i>Mincha</i> would also then be put on the fire. So I think this is an interesting conceptual debate going on here. I think according to the חכמים <i>Chachamim</i>, fundamentally since it's all burned by a כהן <i>Kohen</i>, it's like it's all the קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>, it's all fundamentally the offering to God. Whereas within רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> you could conceptually understand it: no, even by מנחת כהן <i>Minchas kohen</i>, the קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> is fundamentally what is offered to God. Then you have the next question: okay, well the remainder should be eaten by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i>. But because the כהן <i>Kohen</i> is the person himself who is מקריב <i>Makriv</i>, then it can't be eaten by the כהן <i>Kohen</i>. It's supposed to be eaten by somebody other than the owner. So I mean it could be a different כהן <i>Kohen</i>, but conceptually, some a different category than the owner, and therefore it's eaten by the fire. But the fire eating it is separate than it being offered on the fire. I think that is sort of what רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> might be getting at. Okay, let's take a look at the גמרא <i>Gemara</i>. אמר רב פפא כל היכא דתנן עשר תנן <i>Amar Rav Papa: Kol heikha de-tenan eser tenan</i>. Now the גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says this a lot of times. רב פפא <i>Rav Papa</i> says: wherever the משנה <i>Mishna</i> lists מנחות <i>Menachos</i>, it lists ten. מאי קא משמע לן <i>Mai kamashma lan</i>? What is this coming to teach us? לאפוקי רבי שמעון דאמר מחצה חלות ומחצה רקיקין יביא קא משמע לן דלא <i>Le-apukei Rabbi Shimon de-amar mechtza chalos mechtza rekikhin yavi, kamashma lan de-lo</i>: to exclude the position of רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> that says that a מנחה מאפה תנור <i>Mincha ma-afeh tanur</i> is not only that it could be ten חלות <i>Chalos</i> or ten רקיקין <i>Rekikhin</i>, it could also be five and five. So רב פפא <i>Rav Papa</i> is telling us that the משנה <i>Mishna</i> rejects that. Now how is the משנה <i>Mishna</i> rejecting it and what does he mean by ten? So you'll remember that רש״י <i>Rashi</i> gives two explanations. One is: there are ten מנחות <i>Menachos</i> that are listed in these lists. Okay, let's talk about them: סולת מחבת מרחשת חלות רקיקין <i>Solet, machavas, marcheshes, chalos, rekikhin</i>, that's five; עובדי כוכבים נשים עומר חוטא קנאות <i>Ovdei kokhavim, nashim, omer, chotei, kena'os</i>, that's another five. That's ten. So he's saying there are only ten מנחות <i>Menachos</i> and according to רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> you would have an eleventh. What would the eleventh be? Something that is half רקיקין <i>Rekikhin</i> and half חלות <i>Chalos</i>. So because it says ten, it's implicitly refuting or rejecting רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i>'s position. The other way of saying it is that he's just making a claim that all of these get ten full loaves for each category, and for רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i> the case of חלות <i>Chalos</i> and רקיקין <i>Rekikhin</i> would get five loaves of each. The first read is probably a better one. ושיריהן לכהנים <i>Ve-shiyureihen la-kohanim</i>: and the remainder of these ones that you do the קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i> are eaten by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i>. מנלן <i>Menalan</i>? Where do you learn this from? So the גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says: where do you learn it from? דכתיבא כתיבא <i>De-chtiva chtiva</i>, the ones that say it explicitly, take a קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>, burn the קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>, the remainder is eaten, say it explicitly; ודלא כתיבא כתיבא בי <i>U-delo chtiva chtiva bi</i>, and the ones that are not written explicitly, you still have a general פסוק <i>Pasuk</i> that's written in צו <i>Tzav</i>: וזאת תהיה תורת המנחה <i>Ve-zos tihye toras hamincha</i>, this will be the law of the מנחה <i>Mincha</i>. So תורה <i>Torah</i> means it's like a category, it applies to all the מנחות <i>Menachos</i>. הקרב אותה בני אהרן <i>Hakrev osah bnei Aharon</i>, the children of Aaron should offer it up. And then it says: והנותרת ממנה יאכלו אהרן ובניו <i>Ve-hanoseres mimena yokhlu Aharon u-vanav</i>: what remains is eaten by Aaron and his children. So very clear that the rule of כהנים <i>Kohanim</i> is when there's a קמיצה <i>Kmitzah</i>, what remains is eaten by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i>. Aaron and the children. So the question might be, okay, is it explicit that you do קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> for everything? So let's see where the גמרא <i>Gemara</i> goes. So the גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says like this, so you know רש"י <i>Rashi</i> here lists, you know, the various מנחות <i>menachos</i> why it says קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> and we can sort of assume קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> is said by all the מנחות <i>menachos</i> and therefore if there's a קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> implicitly the remainder is eaten by, you know, by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i> or not implicitly, explicitly from וזאת תורת המנחה <i>V'zos toras haminchah</i>. By the way, I should note something, on all these דפים <i>dappim</i> here and, you know, a little bit of the few פרקים <i>prakim</i> moving forward, you'll see that it also says רש"י כתב יד <i>Rashi Kesav Yad</i>. Because the publisher, you know, we don't always fully appreciate, how did we get this תוספות <i>Tosafos</i> on the side, this רש"י <i>Rashi</i> on the side? The publisher had to decide, there were different types, there were different תוספות <i>Tosafists</i> from the different schools. He had to decide which school of the תוספות <i>Tosafists</i> you're going to use, which manuscript you're going to use. So the person, you know, when they came to putting the גמרא <i>Gemara</i>, by the time they came to this version of the גמרא <i>Gemara</i>, they had found a different manuscript of רש"י <i>Rashi</i> that claimed that the רש"י <i>Rashi</i> that we have in the slightly larger font, which had been there originally, is not the original רש"י <i>Rashi</i> and the one in the manuscript is the original רש"י <i>Rashi</i>. It seems to be that that is the case because when תוספות <i>Tosafos</i> cites רש"י <i>Rashi</i>, it parallels what's in the smaller רש"י <i>Rashi</i> where it says רש"י כתב יד <i>Rashi Kesav Yad</i> and not what's in the bigger רש"י <i>Rashi</i> that was originally, you know, the only רש"י <i>Rashi</i> that was on the page. Anyway, okay, so רש"י <i>Rashi</i> points out, you know, that there are, it says it by the קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> and therefore once it says קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> based on this פסוק <i>pasuk</i> you can assume the הנצום <i>hanatzum</i>, the שיריים <i>shirayim</i> are eaten by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i>. So the גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says no here's our question. The גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says like this, בהא לא קמיבעיא לן <i>Behai lo kamibaya lan</i>, we're not asking about what happens by a מנחה <i>minchah</i> that is coming from, from flour, you know, from wheat flour, because that's the standard וזאת תורת המנחה <i>V'zos toras haminchah</i>, the standard מנחות <i>menachos</i> listed in ויקרא <i>Vayikra</i> and צו <i>Tzav</i> are ones out of wheat flour. כי קמיבעיא לן דשעורים <i>Ki kamibaya lan d'seorim</i>, our question is the ones that come out of barley, how do you know those are also included in וזאת תורת המנחה <i>V'zos toras haminchah</i>? So now, now by the way, תוספות <i>Tosafos</i> points out, sometimes we assume וזאת תורת המנחה <i>V'zos toras haminchah</i> includes all מנחות <i>menachos</i> we don't care wheat or barley. But here maybe we think specifically it might be limited to wheat, not only because those are the standard מנחות <i>menachos</i> we're talking about, but because wheat is normally, you know, wheat flour is normally eaten by people whereas barley flour was standard only fed to animals. So maybe we should not assume that the idea that the remainder is eaten by the כהנים <i>Kohanim</i> applies to the מנחות <i>menachos</i> of barley. So the גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says כי דשעורים נמי מנא ידעינן דשייריא לכהנים <i>Ki d'seorim nami m'na yad'inan d'shayeraya l'kohanim</i>, also so what says the גמרא <i>Gemara</i>, you know, even so, from the very fact that you're doing קמיצה <i>kemitza</i>, even if you don't want to read it into the פסוק <i>pasuk</i>, from the very fact that you do קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> by a מנחה <i>minchah</i> of barley, obviously you're doing קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> so that the, you know, it's assigning a different role to the קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> which is burned and implicitly there's something else happening with the remainder, the remainder is eaten. So it's implicit from the fact of קמיצה <i>kemitza</i>. גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says no, not necessarily, אליבא דרבנן לא קמיבעיא לן <i>Aliba d'Rabbanan lo kamibaya lan</i>, according to the רבנן <i>Rabbanan</i> that say by מנחת כהן <i>minchas kohen</i>, the fact that you do קמיצה <i>kemitza</i>, you know, excuse me, by מנחת כהן <i>minchas kohen</i>, you know, you can never have it that you do קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> and burn the remainder, and therefore for מנחת כהן <i>minchas kohen</i> they burn the whole thing, they would never split, they would never sort of, you know, say that. For them clearly if there's קמיצה <i>kemitza</i>, you're going to eat the remainder and that's why by מנחת כהן <i>minchas kohen</i> where it's not eaten there's no קמיצה <i>kemitza</i>. כי קמיבעיא לן אליבא דרבי שמעון <i>Ki kamibaya lan aliba d'Rabbi Shimon</i>, but our question is according to רבי שמעון <i>Rabbi Shimon</i>, דאמר איכא מנחה דמקמצה ולא מתאכלה <i>d'amar ika minchah d'mikamtza v'lo misachla</i>, he says you can have a case of קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> where the remainder isn't eaten, מנחת כהנים <i>minchas kohanim</i>. So the very fact that the תורה <i>Torah</i> writes קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> doesn't by itself prove that the remainder is eaten and maybe the by barley the remainder wouldn't be eaten, maybe it wouldn't be included in וזאת תורת המנחה <i>V'zos toras haminchah</i>. דתנן רבי שמעון אומר מנחת חוטא של כהנים נקמצת והקומץ קרב בעצמו והשיריים קרבים בעצמם <i>D'tenan Rabbi Shimon omer minchas chotei shel kohanim nikmetzes v'hakometz karev b'atzmo v'hashirayim krevim b'atzmam</i>. So he says by מנחת כהן <i>minchas kohen</i> you can have not eat the remainder, the remainder could also be burned and you could do a קמיצה <i>kemitza</i> by מנחת כהן <i>minchas kohen</i>. So מנלן <i>m'nalan</i>, so where do we know it from? אמר חזקיה דאמר קרא <i>Amar Chizkiyah d'amar kra</i>, the פסוק <i>pasuk</i> says וכל מנחה בלולה בשמן וחרבה <i>V'chol minchah belulah vashamen vacharevah</i>, any מנחה <i>minchah</i> that is mixed with, you know, oil or that is dry, לכל בני אהרן תהיה איש כדאחיו <i>l'chol b'nei Aharon tihyeh ish k'achiv</i>, it should be for all בני אהרן <i>b'nei Aharon</i>, it should be equally eaten by all of them. This is an interesting פסוק <i>pasuk</i> in צו <i>Tzav</i> where it seems to indicate a different type of division based on which type of מנחה <i>minchah</i> it is. The פסוק <i>pasuk</i> there says as follows, it says... actually, no, excuse me, this is actually a פסוק <i>pasuk</i>, yes, excuse me, it is in צו <i>Tzav</i>, it's just a little later, it's in זיין <i>Zayin</i>, it says like this, it says וכל מנחה אשר תאפה <i>v'chol minchah asher teafeh</i> Any מנחה <i>mincha</i> that's in an oven or in a frying pan, you know, saucepan, לכהן המקריב אותה לו תהיה <i>lakohen hamakriv otah lo tihiyeh</i> goes to the כהן <i>kohen</i> who offers it. וכל מנחה בל