he context of a sacrifice might sound even a little pagan maybe דוקא <i>davka</i> with a non-Jewish idea. But anyway, that is one explanation that they think it has to be fully to God. So even when they say שלמים <i>shlamim</i>, they're just assuming it's all to God. ואיבעית אימא <i>Ve'iba'it eima</i>, if you want, קרא <i>kra</i> it's a פסוק <i>pasuk</i> because we learn... out non-Jews from איש איש <i>ish ish</i>, and I already sort of, you know, ruined the surprise. The end of the פסוק <i>pasuk</i> is אשר יקריבו להשם לעולה <i>asher yakrivu l'Hashem l'olah</i>, that they offer to God as an עולה <i>olah</i>. So later פסוקים <i>pesukim</i> talk about שלמים <i>shelamim</i>, but this is read as, if a non-Jew is offering it, it is going to be an עולה <i>olah</i>. כל דמקרבי עולה להוי <i>kol demikrevi olah lehavei</i>, whatever they offer is going to be treated as an עולה <i>olah</i>. All right. So that's the statement. Now we're going to challenge it. מתיב רב חמא בר גוריא <i>metiv Rav Chama bar Guria</i>. So רב חמא בר גוריא <i>Rav Chama bar Guria</i> challenges. One wonders if גוריא <i>Guria</i> means גר <i>ger</i>, and whether he was, sort of had a personal stake in this. Anyway, exactly a stake, but anyway, he challenged it the following way: עובד כוכבים שהתנדב להביא שלמים <i>oved kokhavim shehitnadev lehavi shelamim</i>, if a non-Jew takes a vow to give a שלמים <i>shelamim</i>, so this is a תוספתא <i>Tosefta</i>, נתנם לישראל ישראל אוכלם <i>netanam l'Yisrael Yisrael okhlam</i>, if he gives it to a ישראל <i>Yisrael</i>, the ישראל <i>Yisrael</i> eats it; נתנם לכהן כהן אוכלם <i>netanam l'kohen kohen okhlam</i>, to a כהן <i>kohen</i>, a כהן <i>kohen</i> eats it. So it's a very hard-to-parse teaching. What does it mean he gives them to an Israelite? What it seems to be saying is he can bring a שלמים <i>shelamim</i> but he can't eat it. Okay, we'll take his sacrifice, but to have a non-Jew eating from a קרבן <i>korban</i> in the בית המקדש <i>Beit HaMikdash</i>, that's not acceptable. So you choose. You can give it to a ישראל <i>Yisrael</i> and then it'll be treated as a ישראל <i>Yisrael</i>. You give it to a כהן <i>kohen</i>, maybe then it'll be treated as the portion of a כהן <i>kohen</i>. That seems to be what the ברייתא <i>braita</i> is saying. But anyway, it seems like he can bring a שלמים <i>shelamim</i>. So אמר רבא הכי קאמר <i>amar Rava hachi ka'amar</i>, no no, here's what the ברייתא <i>braita</i> means: על מנת שיתכפרו בהן ישראל ישראל אוכלם <i>al menat sheyitkapru bahen Yisrael Yisrael okhlam</i>, על מנת שיתכפרו בהן כהן כהן אוכלם <i>al menat sheyitkapru bahen kohen kohen okhlam</i>. He can dedicate something as a שלמים <i>shelamim</i> of a ישראל <i>Yisrael</i>. If a ישראל <i>Yisrael</i> has, took a vow to give a שלמים <i>shelamim</i>, a non-Jew can say, let me dedicate my animal, my cow, this cow will be ראובן <i>Reuven</i>'s שלמים <i>shelamim</i>, or let me dedicate it to this כהן <i>kohen</i>, it'll be this כהן <i>kohen</i>'s שלמים <i>shelamim</i>. So even though he owns the cow, it is the sacrifice of the person on whose sake it was dedicated and sanctified and therefore, and then you follow accordingly, but not that the שלמים <i>shelamim</i> can actually be his שלמים <i>shelamim</i>. It could start as his cow, but it's not his שלמים <i>shelamim</i>. Okay. מתיב רב שיזבי <i>metiv Rav Shizbi</i>. So רב שיזבי <i>Rav Shizbi</i> challenged, and this is why we're discussing it here. אלו מנחות נקמצות ושיריהן לכהנים <i>elu menachot nikmatzot v'shiyreihen l'kohanim</i>. Our משנה <i>mishnah</i>, the following מנחות <i>menachot</i> you take a קמיצה <i>kmitzah</i> and the remainder is eaten by the כהנים <i>kohanim</i>. מנחת עובדי כוכבים <i>minchat ovdei kokhavim</i>, and it says non-Jew. So you see a non-Jew can bring a מנחה <i>mincha</i>. And רב הונא <i>Rav Huna</i> is saying a non-Jew can only bring an עולה <i>olah</i>. So it doesn't have the challenge like a שלמים <i>shelamim</i> that the owners would eat it, because here the כהן <i>k