t an עולה <i>olah</i> and not even the stuff that accompanies it. So גמרא <i>Gemara</i> says אי בעית אימא רבי יוסי הגלילי ואי בעית אימא רבי עקיבא <i>ei ba'it eima Rebbe Yosi Haglili ve-ei ba'it eima Rebbe Akiva</i>. It could go according to either. אי בעית אימא רבי יוסי הגלילי <i>ei ba'it eima Rebbe Yosi Haglili</i>, סמי מכאן יין <i>sami mikan yayin</i>. It could be רבי יוסי הגלילי <i>Rebbe Yosi Haglili</i> but let's take off of the list יין <i>yayin</i>. When we have a list that רבי יוסי <i>Rebbe Yosi</i> says הגלילי <i>Haglili</i> says he could bring anything, anything except wine. Now wine would be a bizarre thing to exclude, but maybe that's what we're learning from the word from here אזרח <i>ezrach</i>. The word אזרח <i>ezrach</i> would say even for רבי יוסי הגלילי <i>Rebbe Yosi Haglili</i> a non-Jew could bring anything except wine. Again somewhat bizarre and רבי יוסי הגלילי'ס <i>Rebbe Yosi Haglili's</i> original statement did say wine. So the better answer is the other point. ואי בעית אימא <i>ve-ei ba'it eima</i>, if you want I can tell you, רבי עקיבא <i>Rebbe Akiva</i> is רבי עקיבא <i>Rebbe Akiva</i>. עולה וכל חברתה <i>olah ve-chol chavratah</i>, like we said before, עולה <i>olah</i> and its retinue. So yes according to רבי עקיבא <i>Rebbe Akiva</i> a non-Jew brings an עולה <i>olah</i> with the נסכים <i>nesachim</i>, but any קרבן <i>korban</i> other than an עולה <i>olah</i> and נסכים <i>nesachim</i> by themselves cannot be brought by the non-Jew. Okay we will end here.